        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/poland-baltics-ottawa-treaty-exit.png" alt="A warning sign with a skull and crossbones reading stop mines! in Russian, placed in a snowy field with a demining operation in the background." href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>A field in Kyiv oblast, Ukraine, where a British charity cleared landmines in 2022. Credits: Chris Strickland for The Telegraph/Halo Trust
          </i></p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Poland and the Baltic states, Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania, announced plans to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-20-03-2025-h1-1-withdraw-from-the-ottawa-treaty" target="_blank">withdraw from the Ottawa Treaty</a>, which bans anti-personnel landmines. The announcement comes amid growing threats from Russia and Belarus. In a joint statement, their defense ministers said the security situation has ‚Äúsignificantly deteriorated‚Äù since signing the treaty. They said it is ‚Äúparamount‚Äù to ensure flexibility in defending NATO‚Äôs eastern flank.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The Ottawa Treaty, signed by over 160 countries, took effect in 1997 to ban mines targeting humans. However, Russia, China, the US, and others never signed. Despite exiting the treaty, the four pledged commitment to international humanitarian law and ensuring civilians' protection during the conflict. All four countries are in the NATO alliance and share borders with Russia.
       </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Since Russia‚Äôs full-scale war with Ukraine in 2022, Poland and the Baltics have increased military spending. The Baltic States and Poland are among the highest aid donors to Ukraine by GDP percentage. Ukraine, a signatory to the treaty, has also faced challenges adhering to the treaty during the war. The UN now estimates Ukraine is the most heavily mined country globally.
</p>
