        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Congolese and Rwandan leaders meet</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: DRC President Felix Tshisekedi and Rwandan President Paul Kagame met in Doha for Qatari-mediated talks to ease tensions in eastern DRC. </strong></p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) President Felix Tshisekedi and Rwandan President Paul Kagame held direct talks in Doha. The Qatari-mediated talks <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-20-03-2025-h3-3-addressed-the-ongoing-conflict" target="_blank">addressed the ongoing conflict</a> in the Eastern DRC. The meeting marked their first since Rwanda-backed M23 rebels seized the key cities of Goma and Bukavu. Both leaders called for an ‚Äúimmediate ceasefire‚Äù in a joint state while agreeing to continue dialogue.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The DRC accuses Rwanda of supporting M23 with weapons and troops. Rwanda denies the claims, while the UN reports around 4,000 Rwandan troops backing the rebels. The conflict intensified after M23 withdrew from peace talks in Angola. They backed out over EU sanctions on their leaders and three Rwandan military commanders. M23 said the sanctions ‚Äúseriously compromise direct dialogue and prevent any advance.‚Äù</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">M23 is one of over 100 armed groups operating in the mineral-rich eastern DRC. They have contributed to one of the world‚Äôs worst humanitarian crises, with over 7 Mn displaced. The rebel advance and regional tensions threaten stability across the Great Lakes region.</p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>
