          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>üá∏üáæ Syria and Lebanon agree on ceasefire </strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Lebanon and Syria have <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-20-03-2025-br2-5-agreed-to-a-ceasefire" target="_blank">agreed to a ceasefire</a> after two days of deadly cross-border clashes that killed 10 people and wounded 52 in Lebanon. Lebanese Defense Minister Michel Menassa and Syrian counterpart Murhaf Abu Qasra also agreed to maintain contact between their army intelligence directorates to prevent further escalation. Tensions flared after Syria accused Hezbollah of killing its soldiers, which Hezbollah denies.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">A Lebanese source said the Syrian troops had crossed into Lebanon and were killed by armed tribesmen fearing an attack. In retaliation, Syrian forces shelled Lebanese border towns, which forced residents to flee. Lebanon later returned the bodies of the Syrian soldiers. Syrian troops reinforced positions along the border with tanks.</p>
        </mj-text>
