          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">How did modern Turkey come to be?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/mustafa-kemal-ataturk-modern-turkey.png" alt="A historical black-and-white portrait of Mustafa Kemal Atat√ºrk, the founder of modern Turkey, seated on a patterned couch." href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Mustafa Kemal Atat√ºrk aboard a ship off the coast of Bursa, northwestern T√ºrkiye, June 5, 1926. Credits: AA Photo</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">‚ÄãModern Turkey was founded in 1923 after the collapse of the Ottoman Empire, which had ruled much of the Middle East, North Africa, and southeastern Europe for centuries. The empire sided with Germany in World War I and, after losing, was partitioned by the victorious Allied powers.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The Turkish War of Independence (1919‚Äì1923), led by <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-20-03-2025-f1-6-mustafa-kemal-ataturk" target="_blank">Mustafa Kemal Atat√ºrk</a>, emerged in response to the occupation of Istanbul and the planned division of Turkish lands under the Treaty of S√®vres. Atat√ºrk rallied nationalist forces, expelled foreign troops, and defeated internal opposition. In 1923, the Treaty of Lausanne recognized Turkey's new borders and officially proclaimed the Republic of Turkey.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Atat√ºrk became Turkey's first president. He launched sweeping secular, political, and social reforms to modernize the country and separated religion from the state. His legacy in Turkey is very divided. While many find him to be a hero, others see him as a repressive dictator. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Many ethnic minorities were oppressed during his rule as he cracked down on some of their rebellions. However, many are divided on how much of it is accurate, and some dismiss these claims as anti-Turkish propaganda.</p>
          
